# matter.word — what a MATTER is, has, and can. A thing in a space, of a type.
# Bottoms out in the host (seed/materials/matter/, the type registry and schema). Descends from
# word.word, base.word, chain.word, fold.word, name.word, being.word, space.word. A type is the
# extension point: each names its content and its dos. `qualities` grounds in the cluster. A kind
# stays lowercase. set, end, purge, rename are matter's own dos, grounded here.

A matter is a thing in a space.
A matter has a type, its kind.
A generic matter has text, or no content. It can be set and ended.
A file matter has text or bytes. It can be set, ended, and purged.
A model matter has bytes, a glb or gltf. It can be set, ended, and purged.
An http matter has a web address, and no content. It can be set and ended.
A source matter has text, bytes, or none. It can be made, set, ended, and renamed.
An ibpa matter has a portal address, and no content. It can be set and ended.
A connection matter has no content. It can be set and ended.
A matter has an id, the hash of its birth.
A matter has an owner, the being that made it.
A matter has a name, unique among the matter beside it.
A matter has content, of its type.
A matter has qualities.
A matter has a position, the space it is in, and a point in it.
A matter may have a parent, the matter above it, and children below.
A matter can be made, set, renamed, ended, and its content purged.
